:"1420–1500","1422–1450":"1422–1450","1450–1470":"1450–1470","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1420":"1420","Aft 1419":"after 1419","1450":"1450","after 1450":"after 1450","1470":"1470","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Combe Martin, North Devon distirct, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Combe Martin, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Combe Martin, Devon, England":"Combe Martin, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Channon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Cannon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cannon","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Canann</b> or <b>Ó Canáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cano</i> or <i>Canán</i>’. Occasionally, and in the Isle of Man, the surname derives from <i>Mac Canann</i> ‘son of <i>Cano</i> or <i>Canán</i>’, which in Ireland was Anglicized   McCann   or   McConnon  . See also   Connon  . The personal name is from Gaelic <i>cano</i> ‘wolf cub’, of which <i>Canán</i> is a diminutive. In Ulster Cannon may also be shortened from <b>Ó Canannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Canannán’</i>, a pet form (double diminutive) of the personal name. This was a cheiftan family in Donegal, and the name was particularly common there.","English: from Middle English <i>canun</i> ‘canon’ (Old Norman French <i>canonie</i>, <i>canoine</i>, from Late Latin <i>canonicus</i>). In medieval England this term denoted a clergyman living with others in a clergy house; the surname is mostly an occupational name for a servant in a house of canons, although it could also be a nickname or even a patronymic.","French: variant of   Canon  ."]},{"name":"Channing","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Channon  , see   Cannon  .","History: The earliest American Channing was John, who came from Dorset, England, in 1711 with his wife. Their son John became a prosperous merchant of Newport, RI, and their grandson William Ellery was born there in 1780. William Ellery Channing (1780–1842) was a Unitarian clergyman who founded the Massachusetts Peace Society, a precursor of the modern anti-war movement."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Channon was born in 1420, in Combe Martin, Devon, England, his father, Hugh Channon, was 40 and his mother, Elizabeth Martin, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Lady Elizabeth Martin Baroness. He died in 1500, in Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 80, and was buried in Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1420–1500":"1420–1500","1422–1450":"1422–1450","1450–1470":"1450–1470","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1420":"1420","Aft 1419":"pärast 1419","1450":"1450","after 1450":"pärast 1450","1470":"1470","1419":"1419